    notes:
      "## Clinical Context — The Foundational Copper Peptide\n\nGHK-Cu is the principal copper peptide compound and the foundational compound for the broader copper peptide research and cosmetic ingredient category. The compound has substantial research literature dating to Loren Pickart's 1973 isolation work, and the cosmetic ingredient industry has used GHK-Cu formulations for decades — Skin Biology (Pickart's company) has been the commercial reference point for copper peptide skincare since the 1980s.\n\nThe research peptide community use of GHK-Cu spans wound healing, anti-aging, hair regrowth, and tissue repair contexts. The systemic SubQ injectable route is the principal research peptide community application; the topical route is covered separately in the ghk-cu-skin tile.\n\n## The Native Peptide Context\n\nGHK-Cu is endogenous in human plasma at ~200 ng/mL in young adults, declining progressively with age. The age-associated decline parallels broader declines in tissue repair capacity, collagen synthesis, and wound healing efficiency — and the GHK-Cu replacement hypothesis (that supplementing the declining native peptide can restore tissue repair capacity) is the principal mechanistic rationale for therapeutic use.\n\nThe native peptide context distinguishes GHK-Cu from purely pharmacological compounds: the body produces and uses GHK-Cu naturally, and supplementation operates within physiologic pathways rather than introducing entirely novel signaling.\n\n## The Copper Transport Mechanism\n\nThe copper(II) binding architecture is the central pharmacological distinction of GHK-Cu vs unbound GHK tripeptide. Copper is an essential cofactor for numerous enzymes:\n\n| Enzyme | Function | Tissue context |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cu/Zn SOD | Antioxidant defense | All cells |\n| Lysyl oxidase | Collagen/elastin cross-linking | Connective tissue, skin |\n| Tyrosinase | Melanin synthesis | Skin, hair |\n| Dopamine β-hydroxylase | Catecholamine metabolism | CNS, adrenal |\n| Cytochrome c oxidase | Mitochondrial respiration | All cells |\n| DNA repair enzymes | Genome stability | All cells |\n\nGHK delivers bioavailable copper to tissues requiring it, supporting these enzyme systems with localized targeted delivery vs systemic copper supplementation.\n\n## Wound Healing — The Best-Established Use Case\n\nGHK-Cu's wound healing effects are the most thoroughly validated effect in the research literature:\n- Fibroblast proliferation and migration\n- Collagen synthesis stimulation\n- Glycosaminoglycan synthesis\n- Decorin production (collagen organization)\n- Angiogenesis support\n- MMP/TIMP balance modulation (controlled tissue remodeling)\n- Reduced scarring vs untreated wounds\n\nThe wound healing use case applies across acute wounds, surgical recovery, scar remodeling, and chronic wound contexts.\n\n## Hair Regrowth — The Cosmetic Industry Use Case\n\nGHK-Cu's hair follicle effects are the substrate for substantial cosmetic and research peptide community use:\n- Dermal papilla cell stimulation\n- Vellus-to-terminal hair conversion (the principal effect in androgenetic alopecia contexts)\n- Some 5α-reductase inhibitory activity reported\n- Hair shaft thickening reported in cosmetic formulation studies\n\n**Important framing:** GHK-Cu is NOT FDA-approved for alopecia. Pharmaceutical alternatives — minoxidil (topical, FDA-approved for androgenetic alopecia) and finasteride (oral, FDA-approved for male androgenetic alopecia) — have more thoroughly validated efficacy and well-characterized safety profiles. Users with significant clinical alopecia should consider pharmaceutical alternatives or combination approaches with prescriber coordination.\n\n## Synergies\n**BPC-157, TB-500** — combination tissue-repair peptide stacking is common in research peptide community contexts; each compound has distinct mechanism (BPC-157: angiogenesis and gut repair; TB-500: actin sequestration and broad tissue repair; GHK-Cu: copper transport and matrix remodeling); combinations are not catalog-recommended at specific doses per locked rule. **GHK-Cu Topical (ghk-cu-skin)** — adjacent tile for topical cosmetic use; combination with systemic GHK-Cu is common for skin-focused protocols. **Comprehensive nutrition** with adequate copper, zinc, vitamin C (collagen synthesis cofactor), and amino acid availability.\n\n## Topical vs Systemic — Why Two Tiles\n\nThe catalog separates GHK-Cu into two tiles (this systemic injectable tile + ghk-cu-skin topical tile) intentionally:\n\n| Dimension | ghk-cu (systemic SubQ) | ghk-cu-skin (topical) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Route | SubQ injection | Topical cream/serum |\n| Bioavailability | Direct systemic absorption | Localized skin penetration |\n| Use case | Wound healing, hair, tissue repair, anti-aging | Skin quality, fine lines, localized cosmetic |\n| Regulatory | Research peptide / compounding | Cosmetic ingredient (widely accepted) |\n| Sourcing | Research peptide vendors / compounding | Commercial skincare (Skin Biology, Neutrogena, others) |\n| Safety profile | Systemic Cu considerations | Localized; minimal systemic absorption |\n| Cost | Per-mg research peptide pricing | Cosmetic skincare pricing |\n\nUsers commonly use both — topical for daily skin maintenance, systemic SubQ for course-based wound healing or hair regrowth applications.\n\n## WADA / Sport Considerations\n\nGHK-Cu is not specifically named on the WADA Prohibited List as of catalog last update. The broader 'peptide hormones, growth factors, related substances and mimetics' category (Section S2) warrants careful review for any compound with growth-factor-like activity; some governing bodies may interpret GHK-Cu's tissue repair mechanism as falling under this category. Athletes subject to drug testing should consult sport-specific rules and consider TUE if uncertain.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-characterized via decades of research dating to Pickart's 1973 isolation work. Wound healing effects most thoroughly validated in research literature with multiple animal model studies and limited human clinical work. Hair regrowth effects well-supported in cosmetic ingredient research. Anti-aging and skin quality effects substantial in cosmetic formulation literature. Long-term safety profile of high-dose chronic systemic use less well-characterized; cosmetic topical use has decades of commercial use base supporting topical safety.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: well-characterized native human peptide; foundational copper transport and wound healing mechanisms; substantial cosmetic ingredient research base; hair follicle effects supported in research literature; not FDA-approved as pharmaceutical. Anecdote: research peptide community use established for wound healing, hair regrowth, and anti-aging applications; cosmetic-grade topical use widespread for decades; community familiarity with low side effect profile and tissue-repair effects. Decision frame: foundational copper peptide compound; native human peptide context distinguishes from purely pharmacological compounds; wound healing is the best-established use case; hair regrowth is well-supported but not FDA-approved (minoxidil/finasteride remain pharmaceutical alternatives); systemic SubQ injectable vs topical cosmetic routes have substantially different use cases and sourcing landscapes; combination with BPC-157 and TB-500 is common in research peptide community tissue-repair contexts.",
