    mechanism:
      "**37-amino-acid α-helical antimicrobial peptide** of the cathelicidin family — the only human cathelicidin, encoded by the CAMP gene and produced as the hCAP-18 precursor protein, which is then proteolytically cleaved by proteinase 3 to yield the mature LL-37 active peptide. The amino acid sequence (LLGDFFRKSKEKIGKEFKRIVQRIKDFLRNLVPRTES) folds into an amphipathic α-helix in membrane environments — the structural basis for its direct antimicrobial mechanism. LL-37 is endogenous in human tissues, produced primarily by neutrophils (released from azurophilic granules during inflammation), keratinocytes (skin), epithelial cells of the lung and gut, and other tissues responding to infection or injury. **Mechanism — direct antimicrobial activity (the foundational effect)**: the amphipathic α-helix structure enables LL-37 to interact selectively with bacterial cell membranes via electrostatic attraction to anionic membrane phosphates and subsequent insertion into the lipid bilayer, producing pore formation and membrane permeabilization that destroys bacterial integrity. Activity spectrum is broad: gram-positive bacteria (Staphylococcus aureus including MRSA, Streptococcus species), gram-negative bacteria (Escherichia coli, Pseudomonas aeruginosa, Klebsiella species), enveloped viruses (influenza, herpes simplex, others), and fungi (Candida species). The mechanism's broad spectrum and membrane-targeting basis produce a low resistance development profile vs conventional antibiotics — bacteria cannot easily evolve resistance to membrane disruption mechanisms. **Mechanism — anti-biofilm activity**: LL-37 disrupts established biofilms and inhibits biofilm formation — a clinically meaningful property for chronic infection contexts where biofilm-protected bacteria evade conventional antibiotic therapy. **Mechanism — anti-endotoxin (LPS) effects**: LL-37 binds bacterial LPS (lipopolysaccharide) directly, neutralizing endotoxin signaling and reducing the inflammatory cascade triggered by LPS in sepsis and severe infection contexts. The anti-LPS effect is the principal mechanism behind LL-37's investigation as a sepsis adjunct. **Mechanism — immune modulation (the dual-edge effect)**: LL-37 functions as a host defense peptide with broad immune modulatory effects: chemokine induction (CXCL1, CXCL5, CCL20 — driving neutrophil and lymphocyte recruitment), dendritic cell activation, modulation of Toll-like receptor signaling, and recruitment of innate immune effectors. The immune modulatory effects are dose-dependent and context-dependent — at controlled levels, LL-37 supports productive antimicrobial immune response; at supraphysiologic levels or in autoimmune-prone tissue, LL-37 can contribute to pathologic inflammation (discussed in autoimmune section below). **Mechanism — wound healing**: LL-37 supports wound healing via keratinocyte migration stimulation, angiogenesis (new blood vessel formation in healing tissue), and re-epithelialization of damaged skin and mucosal surfaces. The wound healing role complements the antimicrobial role in the native physiologic context — wounds are infection-prone, and LL-37 simultaneously fights infection and supports tissue repair. **Mechanism — vitamin D-LL-37 axis (the native physiology context)**: vitamin D receptor activation upregulates LL-37 expression — a well-established mechanism connecting vitamin D status to antimicrobial defense capacity. The vitamin D-LL-37 axis is the principal mechanism behind vitamin D's documented antimicrobial effects and the rationale for vitamin D status optimization as antimicrobial defense support. Vitamin D deficiency reduces baseline LL-37 production, contributing to increased susceptibility to respiratory infections, tuberculosis, and other infections in deficient populations. **Mechanism — autoimmune disease pathogenesis (the pathologic side)**: LL-37 has been implicated in psoriasis pathogenesis as an autoantigen — LL-37 binds nucleic acids (host DNA/RNA fragments from damaged cells) forming complexes that activate plasmacytoid dendritic cells via TLR9, driving the IFN-α-mediated inflammatory cascade central to psoriasis. LL-37-anti-LL-37 antibodies have been identified in psoriasis patients. Similar mechanisms have been implicated in lupus (SLE) and rosacea. The autoimmune disease pathogenesis is the principal safety consideration for supraphysiologic LL-37 administration — users with personal or family history of psoriasis, rosacea, or systemic autoimmune disease should approach LL-37 with appropriate caution. **Pharmaceutical status**: NOT FDA-approved as of catalog last update; research peptide format is the available form for off-label use. Clinical research has investigated LL-37 in cystic fibrosis (anti-Pseudomonas activity), sepsis (anti-LPS effect), wound healing (chronic and infected wounds), and other indications. **Pharmacokinetics**: SubQ or IM administration; specific PK parameters less well-characterized than for pharmaceutical-developed peptides; daily or several-times-weekly dosing in research peptide community contexts.",
